host by sending SNMP requests with the OID 1.3.6.1.2.1.1.1.

remote host, or to change the configuration of the remote system (if

default community string.

25.Name: SSH Server CBC Mode Ciphers Enabled
25.Synopsis: The SSH server is configured to use Cipher Block Chaining.
25.Description:
The SSH server is configured to support Cipher Block Chaining (CBC)
encryption.  This may allow an attacker to recover the plaintext message
from the ciphertext. 
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server and
does not check for vulnerable software versions.
25.Solution:
Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable CBC mode
cipher encryption, and enable CTR or GCM cipher mode encryption.

27.Name: SNMP 'GETBULK' Reflection DDoS
27.Synopsis:
The remote SNMP daemon is affected by a vulnerability that allows a
reflected distributed denial of service attack.
27.Description:
The remote SNMP daemon is responding with a large amount of data to a
'GETBULK' request with a larger than normal value for
'max-repetitions'. A remote attacker can use this SNMP server to
conduct a reflected distributed denial of service attack on an
arbitrary remote host.
27.Solution:
Disable the SNMP service on the remote host if you do not use it.
Otherwise, restrict and monitor access to this service, and consider
changing the default 'public' community string.
27.Plugin Output:
Nessus was able to determine the SNMP service can be abused in an SNMP
Reflection DDoS attack :
  Request size  (bytes) : 42
  Response size (bytes) : 2028

28.Name: Ethernet MAC Addresses
28.Synopsis:
This plugin gathers MAC addresses from various sources and
consolidates them into a list.
28.Description:
This plugin gathers MAC addresses discovered from both remote probing
of the host (e.g. SNMP and Netbios) and from running local checks
(e.g. ifconfig). It then consolidates the MAC addresses into a single,
unique, and uniform list.

29.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
29.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
29.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
29.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

30.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
30.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
30.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

32.Name: SSH SHA-1 HMAC Algorithms Enabled
32.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
32.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
Although NIST has formally deprecated use of SHA-1 for digital signatures, SHA-1 is still considered secure for HMAC as
the security of HMAC does not rely on the underlying hash function being resistant to collisions.
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the remote SSH server.

The following server-to-client SHA-1 Hash-based Message Authentication Code (HMAC) algorithms are supported :

33.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
33.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
33.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
  gss-gex-sha1-*
  gss-group1-sha1-*
  gss-group14-sha1-*
  rsa1024-sha1
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.
33.Solution: Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable the weak algorithms.
33.Plugin Output:
The following weak key exchange algorithms are enabled : 
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1

reflected distributed denial of service attack.

'max-repetitions'. A remote attacker can use this SNMP server to
conduct a reflected distributed denial of service attack on an
arbitrary remote host.

Otherwise, restrict and monitor access to this service, and consider
changing the default 'public' community string.

63.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
63.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
63.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
63.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

64.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
64.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
64.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by

98.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
98.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
98.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.

134.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
134.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
134.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
134.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

reflected distributed denial of service attack.

170.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
170.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
170.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

204.Synopsis:
The remote SNMP daemon is affected by a vulnerability that allows a
reflected distributed denial of service attack.
204.Description:
The remote SNMP daemon is responding with a large amount of data to a
'GETBULK' request with a larger than normal value for
'max-repetitions'. A remote attacker can use this SNMP server to
conduct a reflected distributed denial of service attack on an
arbitrary remote host.
204.Solution:
Disable the SNMP service on the remote host if you do not use it.
Otherwise, restrict and monitor access to this service, and consider
changing the default 'public' community string.
204.Plugin Output:
Nessus was able to determine the SNMP service can be abused in an SNMP
Reflection DDoS attack :
  Request size  (bytes) : 42
  Response size (bytes) : 2028

205.Name: Ethernet MAC Addresses
205.Synopsis:
This plugin gathers MAC addresses from various sources and
consolidates them into a list.
205.Description:
This plugin gathers MAC addresses discovered from both remote probing
of the host (e.g. SNMP and Netbios) and from running local checks
(e.g. ifconfig). It then consolidates the MAC addresses into a single,
unique, and uniform list.

206.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
206.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
206.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
206.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

207.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
207.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
207.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

209.Name: SSH SHA-1 HMAC Algorithms Enabled
209.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
209.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
Although NIST has formally deprecated use of SHA-1 for digital signatures, SHA-1 is still considered secure for HMAC as
the security of HMAC does not rely on the underlying hash function being resistant to collisions.
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the remote SSH server.

210.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
210.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
210.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
  gss-gex-sha1-*
  gss-group1-sha1-*
  gss-group14-sha1-*
  rsa1024-sha1
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.
210.Solution: Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable the weak algorithms.

213.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
213.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
213.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.
Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
213.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
213.Plugin Output: The remote clock is synchronized with the local clock.

218.Name: Web Server HTTP Header Internal IP Disclosure
218.Synopsis: This web server leaks a private IP address through its HTTP headers.
218.Description:
This may expose internal IP addresses that are usually hidden or
masked behind a Network Address Translation (NAT) Firewall or proxy
server.

configuration. This may also affect other web servers, web applications,
web proxies, load balancers and through a variety of misconfigurations
related to redirection.

227.Name: Open Port Re-check
227.Synopsis: Previously open ports are now closed.
227.Description:
One of several ports that were previously open are now closed or
unresponsive.
There are several possible reasons for this :
  - The scan may have caused a service to freeze or stop
    running.
  - An administrator may have stopped a particular service
    during the scanning process.
This might be an availability problem related to the following :
  - A network outage has been experienced during the scan,
    and the remote network cannot be reached anymore by the
    scanner.
  - This scanner may has been blacklisted by the system
    administrator or by an automatic intrusion detection /
    prevention system that detected the scan.
  - The remote host is now down, either because a user
    turned it off during the scan or because a select denial
    of service was effective.
In any case, the audit of the remote host might be incomplete and may
need to be done again.
227.Plugin Output: Port 4001 was detected as being open but is now closed

231.Description:

quick even against a firewalled target. 
Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.

282.Name: Strict Transport Security (STS) Detection
282.Synopsis: The remote web server implements Strict Transport Security.
282.Description:
The remote web server implements Strict Transport Security (STS).
The goal of STS is to make sure that a user does not accidentally
downgrade the security of his or her browser.
All unencrypted HTTP connections are redirected to HTTPS.  The browser
is expected to treat all cookies as 'secure' and to close the
connection in the event of potentially insecure situations.

The STS header line is :
Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=15552000; includeSubDomains

284.Name: SSL Medium Strength Cipher Suites Supported (SWEET32)
284.Synopsis: The remote service supports the use of medium strength SSL ciphers.
284.Description:
The remote host supports the use of SSL ciphers that offer medium
strength encryption. Nessus regards medium strength as any encryption
that uses key lengths at least 64 bits and less than 112 bits, or 
else that uses the 3DES encryption suite.
Note that it is considerably easier to circumvent medium strength
encryption if the attacker is on the same physical network.
284.Solution:
Reconfigure the affected application if possible to avoid use of
medium strength ciphers.

287.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
287.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
287.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
287.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
287.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : CN=inetaicluster.icp
|-Issuer  : CN=inetaicluster.icp

288.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
288.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
288.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
288.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
288.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : CN=kubernetes-master
|-Issuer  : CN=127.0.0.1@1530177897

316.Name: SNMP 'GETBULK' Reflection DDoS
316.Synopsis:
The remote SNMP daemon is affected by a vulnerability that allows a
reflected distributed denial of service attack.
316.Description:
The remote SNMP daemon is responding with a large amount of data to a
'GETBULK' request with a larger than normal value for
'max-repetitions'. A remote attacker can use this SNMP server to
conduct a reflected distributed denial of service attack on an
arbitrary remote host.
316.Solution:
Disable the SNMP service on the remote host if you do not use it.
Otherwise, restrict and monitor access to this service, and consider
changing the default 'public' community string.

317.Name: SSL/TLS Diffie-Hellman Modulus <= 1024 Bits (Logjam)
317.Synopsis:
The remote host allows SSL/TLS connections with one or more
Diffie-Hellman moduli less than or equal to 1024 bits.
317.Description:
The remote host allows SSL/TLS connections with one or more
Diffie-Hellman moduli less than or equal to 1024 bits. Through
cryptanalysis, a third party may be able to find the shared secret in
a short amount of time (depending on modulus size and attacker
resources). This may allow an attacker to recover the plaintext or
potentially violate the integrity of connections.
317.Solution:
Reconfigure the service to use a unique Diffie-Hellman moduli of 2048
bits or greater.

318.Name: HSTS Missing From HTTPS Server
318.Synopsis: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS.
318.Description:
The remote HTTPS server is not enforcing HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS). 
HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
318.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.
318.Plugin Output:

  "Strict-Transport-Security" header.

329.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
329.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
329.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
329.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
329.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

331.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
331.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
331.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
331.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

332.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
332.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
332.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

352.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
352.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
352.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.
Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
352.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

369.Name: Wireless Access Point Detection
369.Synopsis: The remote host is a wireless access point.
369.Description:
Nessus has determined that the remote host is a wireless access point
(AP).
Ensure that proper physical and logical controls are in place for its
use. A misconfigured access point may allow an attacker to gain access
to an internal network without being physically present on the
premises. If the access point is using an 'off-the-shelf'
configuration (such as 40 or 104 bit WEP encryption), the data being
passed through the access point may be vulnerable to hijacking or
sniffing.
369.Plugin Output:
Nessus has determined that this device is an access point based on a
phrase found on the server's default web page. That is, Nessus
maintains a list of commonly-used technical phrases which can be
associated with wireless technologies. When Nessus encounters these
phrases during a scan, a determination is made regarding the nature of
the device. In this case, Nessus has determined that the device may
be running a wireless device with an administrative interface enabled. 
This is a very common configuration for Access Points. The exact
phrases which Nessus flagged on were :
  - 2.412
  - 2.417
  - 2.422
  - 2.427
  - 2.437

371.Name: HTTP TRACE / TRACK Methods Allowed
371.Synopsis: Debugging functions are enabled on the remote web server.
371.Description:
The remote web server supports the TRACE and/or TRACK methods. TRACE
and TRACK are HTTP methods that are used to debug web server
connections.
371.Solution: Disable these HTTP methods. Refer to the plugin output for more information.
371.Plugin Output:
To disable these methods, add the following lines for each virtual
host in your configuration file :
    RewriteEngine on
    RewriteCond %{REQUEST_METHOD} ^(TRACE|TRACK)
    RewriteRule .* - [F]

374.Name: Nessus SYN scanner
374.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.
374.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 
Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
374.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.
374.Plugin Output: Port 22/tcp was found to be open

391.Name: Microsoft Windows Installed Hotfixes
391.Synopsis:
It was possible to enumerate installed hotfixes on the remote Windows
host.
391.Description:
Using the supplied credentials, Nessus was able to log into the remote
Windows host, enumerate installed hotfixes, and store them in its
knowledge base for other plugins to use.
391.Plugin Output:
The system root c$ used for this test does not have a working network share over
SMB, or has encountered another error similar to STATUS_BAD_NETWORK_NAME.
As a result, Nessus was not able to determine the missing hotfixes on the remote
host and most SMB checks have been disabled.
Solution : Configure the system root to have an SMB network share which the
scanning account has sufficient credentials to access.

409.Name: Nessus Windows Scan Not Performed with Admin Privileges
409.Synopsis:
The Nessus scan of this host may be incomplete due to insufficient
privileges provided.
409.Description:
The Nessus scanner testing the remote host has been given SMB
credentials to log into the remote host, however these credentials do
not have administrative privileges. 
Typically, when Nessus performs a patch audit, it logs into the remote
host and reads the version of the DLLs on the remote host to determine
if a given patch has been applied or not.  This is the method Microsoft
recommends to determine if a patch has been applied. 
If your Nessus scanner does not have administrative privileges when
doing a scan, then Nessus has to fall back to perform a patch audit
through the registry which may lead to false positives (especially when
using third-party patch auditing tools) or to false negatives (not all
patches can be detected through the registry).
409.Solution:
Reconfigure your scanner to use credentials with administrative
privileges.
409.Plugin Output: It was not possible to connect to '\\INET-AI-ICP-SPS-01\ADMIN$' with the supplied credentials.

416.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
416.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
416.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.
The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD
Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.
As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.
Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.

    /

422.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
422.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
422.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
422.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
422.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : C=us/O=ibm/OU=gpfsgui/CN=INET-AI-ICP-SPS01
|-Issuer  : C=us/O=ibm/OU=gpfsgui/CN=INET-AI-ICP-SPS01

436.Name: SSL/TLS Diffie-Hellman Modulus <= 1024 Bits (Logjam)
436.Synopsis:
The remote host allows SSL/TLS connections with one or more
Diffie-Hellman moduli less than or equal to 1024 bits.
436.Description:
The remote host allows SSL/TLS connections with one or more
Diffie-Hellman moduli less than or equal to 1024 bits. Through
cryptanalysis, a third party may be able to find the shared secret in
a short amount of time (depending on modulus size and attacker
resources). This may allow an attacker to recover the plaintext or
potentially violate the integrity of connections.
436.Solution:
Reconfigure the service to use a unique Diffie-Hellman moduli of 2048
bits or greater.

437.Description:

HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
437.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.

439.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
439.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
439.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
439.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
439.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

441.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
441.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
441.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for

authentication protocols.

2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.

timestamp replies (14).

502.Name: Nessus Windows Scan Not Performed with Admin Privileges
502.Synopsis:
The Nessus scan of this host may be incomplete due to insufficient
privileges provided.
502.Description:
The Nessus scanner testing the remote host has been given SMB
credentials to log into the remote host, however these credentials do
not have administrative privileges. 
Typically, when Nessus performs a patch audit, it logs into the remote
host and reads the version of the DLLs on the remote host to determine
if a given patch has been applied or not.  This is the method Microsoft
recommends to determine if a patch has been applied. 
If your Nessus scanner does not have administrative privileges when
doing a scan, then Nessus has to fall back to perform a patch audit
through the registry which may lead to false positives (especially when
using third-party patch auditing tools) or to false negatives (not all
patches can be detected through the registry).
502.Solution:
Reconfigure your scanner to use credentials with administrative
privileges.
502.Plugin Output: It was not possible to connect to '\\INET-AI-ICP-SPS02\ADMIN$' with the supplied credentials.

509.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
509.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
509.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.
The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD
Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.

tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'

considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.

necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.

525.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
525.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
525.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

536.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.

attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.

timestamp replies (14).

563.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
563.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
563.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

570.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
570.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
570.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
570.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
570.Plugin Output: The remote clock is synchronized with the local clock.

that uses key lengths at least 64 bits and less than 112 bits, or 
else that uses the 3DES encryption suite.

encryption if the attacker is on the same physical network.

medium strength ciphers.

605.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
605.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
605.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
605.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
621.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.

626.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
626.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
626.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
626.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
626.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

629.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
629.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
629.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

638.Name: nginx 1.9.5 < 1.16.1 / 1.17.x < 1.17.3 Multiple Vulnerabilities
638.Synopsis: The remote web server is affected by multiple denial of service vulnerabilities.
638.Description:
According to its Server response header, the installed version of nginx is 1.9.5 prior to 1.16.1 or 1.17.x prior to
1.17.3. It is, therefore, affected by multiple denial of service vulnerabilities :

  - A denial of service vulnerability exists in the HTTP/2 protocol stack due to improper handling of exceptional
    conditions. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, by manipulating the window size and stream
    priority of a large data request, to cause a denial of service condition. (CVE-2019-9511)

  - A denial of service vulnerability exists in the HTTP/2 protocol stack due to improper handling of exceptional
    conditions. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, by creating multiple request streams and
    continually shuffling the priority of the streams, to cause a denial of service condition. (CVE-2019-9513)

  - A denial of service vulnerability exists in the HTTP/2 protocol stack due to improper handling of exceptional
    conditions. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, by sending a stream of headers with a zero length
    header name and zero length header value, to cause a denial of service condition. (CVE-2019-9516)
638.Solution: Upgrade to nginx version 1.16.1 / 1.17.3 or later.
638.Plugin Output:
URL               : http://10.40.1.18/
  Installed version : 1.13.4
  Fixed version     : 1.16.1 / 1.17.3

    conditions. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, by creating multiple request streams and
    continually shuffling the priority of the streams, to cause a denial of service condition. (CVE-2019-9513)

  - A denial of service vulnerability exists in the HTTP/2 protocol stack due to improper handling of exceptional
    conditions. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, by sending a stream of headers with a zero length
    header name and zero length header value, to cause a denial of service condition. (CVE-2019-9516)
643.Solution: Upgrade to nginx version 1.16.1 / 1.17.3 or later.

652.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
652.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
652.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.

This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:

  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1

  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1

  gss-gex-sha1-*

  gss-group1-sha1-*

  gss-group14-sha1-*

  rsa1024-sha1

Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.

that uses key lengths at least 64 bits and less than 112 bits, or 
else that uses the 3DES encryption suite.

encryption if the attacker is on the same physical network.
697.Solution:

medium strength ciphers.

700.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
700.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
700.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.
The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD
Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.
As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.
Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.
700.Plugin Output:
Based on the response to an OPTIONS request :
  - HTTP methods GET HEAD OPTIONS POST are allowed on : 
    /

704.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
704.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
704.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
704.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
704.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : CN=opscenter_oem-ec_ca
|-Issuer  : CN=opscenter_oem-ec_ca

719.Name: SSL RC4 Cipher Suites Supported (Bar Mitzvah)
719.Synopsis: The remote service supports the use of the RC4 cipher.
719.Description:
The remote host supports the use of RC4 in one or more cipher suites.
The RC4 cipher is flawed in its generation of a pseudo-random stream
of bytes so that a wide variety of small biases are introduced into
the stream, decreasing its randomness.
If plaintext is repeatedly encrypted (e.g., HTTP cookies), and an
attacker is able to obtain many (i.e., tens of millions) ciphertexts,
the attacker may be able to derive the plaintext.
719.Solution:
Reconfigure the affected application, if possible, to avoid use of RC4
ciphers. Consider using TLS 1.2 with AES-GCM suites subject to browser
and web server support.

727.Name: SSL/TLS Diffie-Hellman Modulus <= 1024 Bits (Logjam)
727.Synopsis:
The remote host allows SSL/TLS connections with one or more
Diffie-Hellman moduli less than or equal to 1024 bits.
727.Description:
The remote host allows SSL/TLS connections with one or more
Diffie-Hellman moduli less than or equal to 1024 bits. Through
cryptanalysis, a third party may be able to find the shared secret in
a short amount of time (depending on modulus size and attacker
resources). This may allow an attacker to recover the plaintext or
potentially violate the integrity of connections.
727.Solution:
Reconfigure the service to use a unique Diffie-Hellman moduli of 2048
bits or greater.

729.Name: Apache Server ETag Header Information Disclosure
729.Synopsis:
The remote web server is affected by an information disclosure
vulnerability.
729.Description:

vulnerability due to the ETag header providing sensitive information
that could aid an attacker, such as the inode number of requested
files.

inodes in the ETag header calculation. Refer to the linked Apache
documentation for more information.

732.Name: Apache 2.2.x < 2.2.33-dev / 2.4.x < 2.4.26 Multiple Vulnerabilities
732.Synopsis: The remote web server is affected by multiple vulnerabilities.
732.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Apache running on the remote
host is 2.2.x prior to 2.2.33-dev or 2.4.x prior to 2.4.26. It is,
therefore, affected by the following vulnerabilities :
  - An authentication bypass vulnerability exists due to
    third-party modules using the ap_get_basic_auth_pw()
    function outside of the authentication phase. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this to
    bypass authentication requirements. (CVE-2017-3167)
  - A NULL pointer dereference flaw exists due to
    third-party module calls to the mod_ssl
    ap_hook_process_connection() function during an HTTP
    request to an HTTPS port. An unauthenticated, remote
    attacker can exploit this to cause a denial of service
    condition. (CVE-2017-3169)
  - A NULL pointer dereference flaw exists in mod_http2 that
    is triggered when handling a specially crafted HTTP/2
    request. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this to cause a denial of service condition. Note that
    this vulnerability does not affect 2.2.x.
    (CVE-2017-7659)
  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ap_find_token() function due to improper handling of
    header sequences. An unauthenticated, remote attacker
    can exploit this, via a specially crafted header
    sequence, to cause a denial of service condition.
    (CVE-2017-7668)
  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in mod_mime due to
    improper handling of Content-Type response headers. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted Content-Type response header, to cause
    a denial of service condition or the disclosure of
    sensitive information. (CVE-2017-7679)
Note that Nessus has not tested for these issues but has instead
relied only on the application's self-reported version number.
732.Solution: Upgrade to Apache version 2.2.33-dev / 2.4.26 or later.
732.Plugin Output:
URL               : http://10.30.201.10:5555/
  Installed version : 2.2.32
  Fixed version     : 2.2.33

737.Name: Apache 2.2.x < 2.2.34 Multiple Vulnerabilities
737.Synopsis: The remote web server is affected by multiple vulnerabilities.
737.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Apache running on the remote
host is 2.2.x prior to 2.2.34. It is, therefore, affected by the
following vulnerabilities :
  - An authentication bypass vulnerability exists in httpd
    due to third-party modules using the
    ap_get_basic_auth_pw() function outside of the
    authentication phase. An unauthenticated, remote
    attacker can exploit this to bypass authentication
    requirements. (CVE-2017-3167)
  - A denial of service vulnerability exists in httpd due to
    a NULL pointer dereference flaw that is triggered when a
    third-party module calls the mod_ssl
    ap_hook_process_connection() function during an HTTP
    request to an HTTPS port. An unauthenticated, remote
    attacker can exploit this to cause a denial of service
    condition. (CVE-2017-3169)
  - A denial of service vulnerability exists in httpd due to
    an out-of-bounds read error in the ap_find_token()
    function that is triggered when handling a specially
    crafted request header sequence. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this to crash the
    service or force ap_find_token() to return an incorrect
    value. (CVE-2017-7668)
  - A denial of service vulnerability exists in httpd due to
    an out-of-bounds read error in the mod_mime that is
    triggered when handling a specially crafted Content-Type
    response header. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can
    exploit this to disclose sensitive information or cause
    a denial of service condition. (CVE-2017-7679)
  - A denial of service vulnerability exists in httpd due to
    a failure to initialize or reset the value placeholder
    in [Proxy-]Authorization headers of type 'Digest' before
    or between successive key=value assignments by
    mod_auth_digest. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can
    exploit this, by providing an initial key with no '='
    assignment, to disclose sensitive information or cause a
    denial of service condition. (CVE-2017-9788)
Note that Nessus has not tested for these issues but has instead
relied only on the application's self-reported version number.
737.Solution: Upgrade to Apache version 2.2.34 or later.

742.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
742.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
742.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
742.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
742.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

757.Name: SSH SHA-1 HMAC Algorithms Enabled
757.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
757.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
Although NIST has formally deprecated use of SHA-1 for digital signatures, SHA-1 is still considered secure for HMAC as
the security of HMAC does not rely on the underlying hash function being resistant to collisions.
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the remote SSH server.

  hmac-sha1
  hmac-sha1-96
The following server-to-client SHA-1 Hash-based Message Authentication Code (HMAC) algorithms are supported : 
  hmac-sha1
  hmac-sha1-96

758.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
758.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
758.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
  gss-gex-sha1-*
  gss-group1-sha1-*
  gss-group14-sha1-*
  rsa1024-sha1
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.
758.Solution: Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable the weak algorithms.

781.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
781.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
781.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
781.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

782.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
782.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
782.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

806.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
806.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
806.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
806.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

807.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
807.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
807.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.

This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

814.Name: Web Server robots.txt Information Disclosure
814.Synopsis: The remote web server contains a 'robots.txt' file.
814.Description:
The remote host contains a file named 'robots.txt' that is intended to
prevent web 'robots' from visiting certain directories in a website for
maintenance or indexing purposes.  A malicious user may also be able to
use the contents of this file to learn of sensitive documents or
directories on the affected site and either retrieve them directly or
target them for other attacks.
814.Solution:
Review the contents of the site's robots.txt file, use Robots META tags
instead of entries in the robots.txt file, and/or adjust the web
server's access controls to limit access to sensitive material.

819.Name: Nessus SYN scanner

quick even against a firewalled target.

against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.

844.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
844.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
844.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
844.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
844.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : CN=localhost
|-Issuer  : CN=localhost

860.Name: SSL/TLS Diffie-Hellman Modulus <= 1024 Bits (Logjam)
860.Synopsis:
The remote host allows SSL/TLS connections with one or more
Diffie-Hellman moduli less than or equal to 1024 bits.
860.Description:
The remote host allows SSL/TLS connections with one or more
Diffie-Hellman moduli less than or equal to 1024 bits. Through
cryptanalysis, a third party may be able to find the shared secret in
a short amount of time (depending on modulus size and attacker
resources). This may allow an attacker to recover the plaintext or
potentially violate the integrity of connections.
860.Solution:
Reconfigure the service to use a unique Diffie-Hellman moduli of 2048
bits or greater.
