861.Name: HSTS Missing From HTTPS Server
861.Synopsis: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS.
861.Description:
The remote HTTPS server is not enforcing HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS). 
HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
861.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.
861.Plugin Output:
The remote HTTPS server does not send the HTTP
  "Strict-Transport-Security" header.

862.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
862.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
862.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
862.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
862.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

863.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
863.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
863.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
863.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

864.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
864.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
864.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

865.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
865.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
865.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
865.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.
865.Plugin Output: TLSv1.1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

869.Description:

the security of HMAC does not rely on the underlying hash function being resistant to collisions.

870.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
870.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
870.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
  gss-gex-sha1-*
  gss-group1-sha1-*
  gss-group14-sha1-*
  rsa1024-sha1
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.
870.Solution: Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable the weak algorithms.

878.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
878.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
878.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.
Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
878.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
878.Plugin Output: The remote clock is synchronized with the local clock.

890.Name: Nessus SYN scanner
890.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.
890.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 
Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
890.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.
890.Plugin Output: Port 22/tcp was found to be open

924.Name: Strict Transport Security (STS) Detection
924.Synopsis: The remote web server implements Strict Transport Security.
924.Description:

The goal of STS is to make sure that a user does not accidentally
downgrade the security of his or her browser.

is expected to treat all cookies as 'secure' and to close the
connection in the event of potentially insecure situations.

927.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
927.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
927.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.
The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD
Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.
As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.
Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.
927.Plugin Output:
Based on the response to an OPTIONS request :
  - HTTP methods  HEAD  OPTIONS  POST  TRACE GET are allowed on : 
    /

930.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
930.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
930.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
930.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
930.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : C=GB/L=Hursley/O=IBM/OU=SSG/CN=2078/E=support@ibm.com
|-Issuer  : C=GB/L=Hursley/O=IBM/OU=SSG/CN=2078/E=support@ibm.com

934.Name: SSL Session Resume Supported
934.Synopsis: The remote host allows resuming SSL sessions.
934.Description:

performing a full SSL handshake to receive a session ID, and then
reconnecting with the previously used session ID.  If the server
accepts the session ID in the second connection, the server maintains
a cache of sessions that can be resumed.

945.Name: SSL Self-Signed Certificate
945.Synopsis:
The SSL certificate chain for this service ends in an unrecognized
self-signed certificate.
945.Description:
The X.509 certificate chain for this service is not signed by a
recognized certificate authority.  If the remote host is a public host
in production, this nullifies the use of SSL as anyone could establish
a man-in-the-middle attack against the remote host. 
Note that this plugin does not check for certificate chains that end
in a certificate that is not self-signed, but is signed by an
unrecognized certificate authority.
945.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

chain sent by the remote host, but is self-signed and was not
found in the list of known certificate authorities :

959.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
959.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
959.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
959.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for

961.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
961.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
961.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
961.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.
961.Plugin Output: TLSv1.1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

970.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
970.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
970.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be

1002.Name: SNMP 'GETBULK' Reflection DDoS
1002.Synopsis:
The remote SNMP daemon is affected by a vulnerability that allows a
reflected distributed denial of service attack.
1002.Description:
The remote SNMP daemon is responding with a large amount of data to a
'GETBULK' request with a larger than normal value for
'max-repetitions'. A remote attacker can use this SNMP server to
conduct a reflected distributed denial of service attack on an
arbitrary remote host.
1002.Solution:
Disable the SNMP service on the remote host if you do not use it.
Otherwise, restrict and monitor access to this service, and consider
changing the default 'public' community string.

1004.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1004.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1004.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
1004.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

1005.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
1005.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
1005.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target

110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

1036.Name: SNMP 'GETBULK' Reflection DDoS
1036.Synopsis:
The remote SNMP daemon is affected by a vulnerability that allows a
reflected distributed denial of service attack.
1036.Description:
The remote SNMP daemon is responding with a large amount of data to a
'GETBULK' request with a larger than normal value for
'max-repetitions'. A remote attacker can use this SNMP server to
conduct a reflected distributed denial of service attack on an
arbitrary remote host.
1036.Solution:
Disable the SNMP service on the remote host if you do not use it.
Otherwise, restrict and monitor access to this service, and consider
changing the default 'public' community string.
1036.Plugin Output:
Nessus was able to determine the SNMP service can be abused in an SNMP
Reflection DDoS attack :
  Request size  (bytes) : 42
  Response size (bytes) : 2028

1037.Name: Ethernet MAC Addresses
1037.Synopsis:
This plugin gathers MAC addresses from various sources and
consolidates them into a list.
1037.Description:
This plugin gathers MAC addresses discovered from both remote probing
of the host (e.g. SNMP and Netbios) and from running local checks
(e.g. ifconfig). It then consolidates the MAC addresses into a single,
unique, and uniform list.

1038.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1038.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1038.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
1038.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

1039.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
1039.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
1039.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

1041.Name: SSH SHA-1 HMAC Algorithms Enabled
1041.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
1041.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
Although NIST has formally deprecated use of SHA-1 for digital signatures, SHA-1 is still considered secure for HMAC as
the security of HMAC does not rely on the underlying hash function being resistant to collisions.
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the remote SSH server.

The following server-to-client SHA-1 Hash-based Message Authentication Code (HMAC) algorithms are supported :

1042.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
1042.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
1042.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
  gss-gex-sha1-*
  gss-group1-sha1-*
  gss-group14-sha1-*
  rsa1024-sha1
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.
1042.Solution: Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable the weak algorithms.
1042.Plugin Output:
The following weak key exchange algorithms are enabled : 
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1

1046.Name: Web Server robots.txt Information Disclosure
1046.Synopsis: The remote web server contains a 'robots.txt' file.
1046.Description:
The remote host contains a file named 'robots.txt' that is intended to
prevent web 'robots' from visiting certain directories in a website for
maintenance or indexing purposes.  A malicious user may also be able to
use the contents of this file to learn of sensitive documents or
directories on the affected site and either retrieve them directly or
target them for other attacks.
1046.Solution:
Review the contents of the site's robots.txt file, use Robots META tags
instead of entries in the robots.txt file, and/or adjust the web
server's access controls to limit access to sensitive material.

1076.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
1076.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
1076.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
1076.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
1076.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : CN=inethmcdr
|-Issuer  : CN=inethmcdr

1092.Name: SSL/TLS Diffie-Hellman Modulus <= 1024 Bits (Logjam)
1092.Synopsis:
The remote host allows SSL/TLS connections with one or more
Diffie-Hellman moduli less than or equal to 1024 bits.
1092.Description:
The remote host allows SSL/TLS connections with one or more
Diffie-Hellman moduli less than or equal to 1024 bits. Through
cryptanalysis, a third party may be able to find the shared secret in
a short amount of time (depending on modulus size and attacker
resources). This may allow an attacker to recover the plaintext or
potentially violate the integrity of connections.
1092.Solution:
Reconfigure the service to use a unique Diffie-Hellman moduli of 2048
bits or greater.

  Cipher suite     : TLS1_CK_DHE_RSA_WITH_AES_128_CBC_SHA
  Diffie-Hellman MODP size (bits) : 1024
    Warning - This is a known static Oakley Group2 modulus. This may make
    the remote host more vulnerable to the Logjam attack.
  Logjam attack difficulty : Hard (would require nation-state resources)

1093.Name: HSTS Missing From HTTPS Server
1093.Synopsis: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS.
1093.Description:
The remote HTTPS server is not enforcing HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS). 
HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
1093.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.
1093.Plugin Output:
The remote HTTPS server does not send the HTTP
  "Strict-Transport-Security" header.

1094.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
1094.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
1094.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
1094.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
1094.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

1095.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1095.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1095.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
1095.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

1096.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
1096.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
1096.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

1097.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
1097.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
1097.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
1097.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.
1097.Plugin Output: TLSv1.1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

1101.Name: SSH SHA-1 HMAC Algorithms Enabled
1101.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
1101.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
Although NIST has formally deprecated use of SHA-1 for digital signatures, SHA-1 is still considered secure for HMAC as
the security of HMAC does not rely on the underlying hash function being resistant to collisions.
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the remote SSH server.

1102.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
1102.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
1102.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
  gss-gex-sha1-*
  gss-group1-sha1-*
  gss-group14-sha1-*
  rsa1024-sha1
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.
1102.Solution: Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable the weak algorithms.
1102.Plugin Output:
The following weak key exchange algorithms are enabled : 
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1

reflected distributed denial of service attack.

1137.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1137.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1137.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
1137.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

1171.Synopsis:
The remote SNMP daemon is affected by a vulnerability that allows a
reflected distributed denial of service attack.

changing the default 'public' community string.

1173.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1173.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1173.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.

of the host (e.g. SNMP and Netbios) and from running local checks
(e.g. ifconfig). It then consolidates the MAC addresses into a single,
unique, and uniform list.

1209.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1209.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1209.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
1209.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

1210.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
1210.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
1210.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

1213.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
1213.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
1213.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
  gss-gex-sha1-*
  gss-group1-sha1-*
  gss-group14-sha1-*
  rsa1024-sha1
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.
1213.Solution: Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable the weak algorithms.

1248.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
1248.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
1248.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
  gss-gex-sha1-*
  gss-group1-sha1-*
  gss-group14-sha1-*
  rsa1024-sha1
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.
1248.Solution: Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable the weak algorithms.
1248.Plugin Output:
The following weak key exchange algorithms are enabled : 
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1

1253.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1253.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1253.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.
Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1253.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
1253.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is -1 seconds.

1256.Name: Web Server No 404 Error Code Check
1256.Synopsis: The remote web server does not return 404 error codes.
1256.Description:
The remote web server is configured such that it does not return '404
Not Found' error codes when a nonexistent file is requested, perhaps
returning instead a site map, search page or authentication page.
Nessus has enabled some counter measures for this.  However, they
might be insufficient.  If a great number of security holes are
produced for this port, they might not all be accurate.

to requests for non-existent URLs with HTTP code 302
rather than 404. The requested URL was :

1265.Name: Nessus SYN scanner
1265.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.
1265.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 
Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
1265.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.
1265.Plugin Output: Port 22/tcp was found to be open

This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 
Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
1269.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.
1269.Plugin Output: Port 3260/tcp was found to be open

1299.Name: Strict Transport Security (STS) Detection
1299.Synopsis: The remote web server implements Strict Transport Security.
1299.Description:
The remote web server implements Strict Transport Security (STS).
The goal of STS is to make sure that a user does not accidentally
downgrade the security of his or her browser.
All unencrypted HTTP connections are redirected to HTTPS.  The browser
is expected to treat all cookies as 'secure' and to close the
connection in the event of potentially insecure situations.

1302.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
1302.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
1302.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.
The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD
Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.
As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.
Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.
1302.Plugin Output:
Based on the response to an OPTIONS request :
  - HTTP methods  HEAD  OPTIONS  POST  TRACE GET are allowed on : 
    /

software products found on a host. 
Note that if an official CPE is not available for the product, this
plugin computes the best possible CPE based on the information
available from the scan.
1304.Plugin Output:
The remote operating system matched the following CPE : 
  cpe:/o:linux:linux_kernel -> Linux Kernel
Following application CPE's matched on the remote system : 
  cpe:/a:apache:tomcat -> Apache Software Foundation Tomcat
  cpe:/a:ibm:san_volume_controller_software -> IBM SAN Volume Controller software
  cpe:/a:openbsd:openssh:6.6 -> OpenBSD OpenSSH

1305.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
1305.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
1305.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
1305.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
1305.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : C=GB/L=Hursley/O=IBM/OU=SSG/CN=2078/E=support@ibm.com
|-Issuer  : C=GB/L=Hursley/O=IBM/OU=SSG/CN=2078/E=support@ibm.com

1309.Name: SSL Session Resume Supported
1309.Synopsis: The remote host allows resuming SSL sessions.
1309.Description:
This script detects whether a host allows resuming SSL sessions by
performing a full SSL handshake to receive a session ID, and then
reconnecting with the previously used session ID.  If the server
accepts the session ID in the second connection, the server maintains
a cache of sessions that can be resumed.
1309.Plugin Output: This port supports resuming TLSv1 / TLSv1 sessions.

ciphers, which maintain confidentiality even if the key is stolen.
1316.Description:

Forward Secrecy (PFS) encryption.  These cipher suites ensure that
recorded SSL traffic cannot be broken at a future date if the server's
private key is compromised.

1320.Name: SSL Self-Signed Certificate
1320.Synopsis:
The SSL certificate chain for this service ends in an unrecognized
self-signed certificate.
1320.Description:
The X.509 certificate chain for this service is not signed by a
recognized certificate authority.  If the remote host is a public host
in production, this nullifies the use of SSL as anyone could establish
a man-in-the-middle attack against the remote host. 
Note that this plugin does not check for certificate chains that end
in a certificate that is not self-signed, but is signed by an
unrecognized certificate authority.
1320.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
1320.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was found at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but is self-signed and was not
found in the list of known certificate authorities :
|-Subject : C=GB/L=Hursley/O=IBM/OU=SSG/CN=2078/E=support@ibm.com

1334.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1334.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1334.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
1334.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

1335.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
1335.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
1335.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

1336.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
1336.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
1336.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
1336.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.
1336.Plugin Output: TLSv1.1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

1351.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1351.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1351.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1351.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
1351.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 44033 seconds.

1352.Name: RPC portmapper Service Detection
1352.Synopsis: An ONC RPC portmapper is running on the remote host.
1352.Description:
The RPC portmapper is running on this port.

The portmapper allows someone to get the port number of each RPC

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.

1379.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1379.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1379.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

1413.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1413.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1413.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

1449.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1449.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1449.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

1454.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1454.Description:

attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1454.Solution:

timestamp replies (14).

1480.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
1480.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
1480.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
1480.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

1513.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
1513.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
1513.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
1513.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

1518.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1518.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1518.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

1542.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
1542.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
1542.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
1542.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

certificate authority :

1548.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
1548.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
1548.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
1548.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
1548.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

1549.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1549.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1549.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

1558.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1558.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1558.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.
Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1558.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
1558.Plugin Output: The remote clock is synchronized with the local clock.

firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if

1578.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
1578.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
1578.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
1578.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :

1584.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
1584.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
1584.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
1584.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
1584.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

1585.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1585.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1585.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
1585.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on ports 22, 2222 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability

1587.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
1587.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
1587.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
1587.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.

1589.Name: SSH SHA-1 HMAC Algorithms Enabled
1589.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
1589.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
Although NIST has formally deprecated use of SHA-1 for digital signatures, SHA-1 is still considered secure for HMAC as
the security of HMAC does not rely on the underlying hash function being resistant to collisions.
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the remote SSH server.

  hmac-sha1-etm@openssh.com

1590.Name: SSH SHA-1 HMAC Algorithms Enabled
1590.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
1590.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
Although NIST has formally deprecated use of SHA-1 for digital signatures, SHA-1 is still considered secure for HMAC as
the security of HMAC does not rely on the underlying hash function being resistant to collisions.
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the remote SSH server.
1590.Plugin Output:
The following client-to-server SHA-1 Hash-based Message Authentication Code (HMAC) algorithms are supported : 
  hmac-sha1
  hmac-sha1-etm@openssh.com
The following server-to-client SHA-1 Hash-based Message Authentication Code (HMAC) algorithms are supported : 
  hmac-sha1
  hmac-sha1-etm@openssh.com

1591.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
1591.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
1591.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
  gss-gex-sha1-*
  gss-group1-sha1-*
  gss-group14-sha1-*
  rsa1024-sha1
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.
1591.Solution: Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable the weak algorithms.
1591.Plugin Output:
The following weak key exchange algorithms are enabled : 
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1

1593.Name: SSL/TLS Recommended Cipher Suites
1593.Synopsis: The remote host advertises discouraged SSL/TLS ciphers.
1593.Description:
The remote host has open SSL/TLS ports which advertise discouraged cipher suites. It is recommended to only enable
support for the following cipher suites:
TLSv1.3:
  - 0x13,0x01 TLS_AES_128_GCM_SHA256
  - 0x13,0x02 TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384
  - 0x13,0x03 TLS_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256
TLSv1.2:
  - 0xC0,0x2B ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0xC0,0x2F ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0xC0,0x2C ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
  - 0xC0,0x30 ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
  - 0xCC,0xA9 ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305
  - 0xCC,0xA8 ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305
  - 0x00,0x9E DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0x00,0x9F DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
This is the recommended configuration for the vast majority of services, as it is highly secure and compatible with
nearly every client released in the last five (or more) years.
1593.Solution: Only enable support for recommened cipher suites.

1594.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1594.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1594.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.
Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1594.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
1594.Plugin Output: The remote clock is synchronized with the local clock.

1603.Name: Nessus SYN scanner
1603.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.
1603.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 
Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
1603.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.
1603.Plugin Output: Port 22/tcp was found to be open

1613.Name: Apache Tomcat Default Files
1613.Synopsis: The remote web server contains default files.
1613.Description:
The default error page, default index page, example JSPs and/or example servlets are installed on the remote Apache
Tomcat server. These files should be removed as they may help an attacker uncover information about the remote Tomcat
install or host itself.
1613.Solution:
Delete the default index page and remove the example JSP and servlets. Follow the Tomcat or OWASP instructions to 
replace or modify the default error page.
1613.Plugin Output:
The server is not configured to return a custom page in the event of a client requesting a non-existent resource.
This may result in a potential disclosure of sensitive information about the server to attackers.
