1640.Name: SSL Medium Strength Cipher Suites Supported (SWEET32)
1640.Synopsis: The remote service supports the use of medium strength SSL ciphers.
1640.Description:
The remote host supports the use of SSL ciphers that offer medium
strength encryption. Nessus regards medium strength as any encryption
that uses key lengths at least 64 bits and less than 112 bits, or 
else that uses the 3DES encryption suite.
Note that it is considerably easier to circumvent medium strength
encryption if the attacker is on the same physical network.
1640.Solution:
Reconfigure the affected application if possible to avoid use of
medium strength ciphers.

1644.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
1644.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
1644.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.
The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD
Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.
As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.
Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.
1644.Plugin Output:
Based on the response to an OPTIONS request :
  - HTTP methods  DELETE  HEAD  OPTIONS  POST  PUT GET 
    are allowed on : 
    /

1647.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
1647.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
1647.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
1647.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
1647.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was part of the certificate chain
sent by the remote host, but it has expired :
|-Subject   : C=IL/ST=Israel/L=Tel Aviv/O=IBM/OU=XIV/CN=Hyper-Scale Manager
|-Not After : May 18 09:22:00 2019 GMT
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : C=IL/ST=Israel/L=Tel Aviv/O=IBM/OU=XIV/CN=Hyper-Scale Manager
|-Issuer  : C=IL/ST=Israel/L=Tel Aviv/O=IBM/OU=XIV/CN=Hyper-Scale Manager

    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer

    support or does not recognize.

chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.

bits or greater.

Diffie-Hellman moduli less than or equal to 1024 bits.
1681.Description:
The remote host allows SSL/TLS connections with one or more
Diffie-Hellman moduli less than or equal to 1024 bits. Through
cryptanalysis, a third party may be able to find the shared secret in
a short amount of time (depending on modulus size and attacker
resources). This may allow an attacker to recover the plaintext or
potentially violate the integrity of connections.
1681.Solution:
Reconfigure the service to use a unique Diffie-Hellman moduli of 2048
bits or greater.

1684.Name: HSTS Missing From HTTPS Server
1684.Synopsis: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS.
1684.Description:
The remote HTTPS server is not enforcing HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS). 
HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
1684.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.
1684.Plugin Output:
The remote HTTPS server does not send the HTTP
  "Strict-Transport-Security" header.

1685.Name: AMQP Cleartext Authentication
1685.Synopsis:

authentication.
1685.Description:
The remote Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP) service supports
one or more authentication mechanisms that allow credentials to be
sent in the clear.
1685.Solution: Disable cleartext authentication mechanisms in the AMQP configuration.

1686.Name: SSH Weak Algorithms Supported
1686.Synopsis:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak encryption
algorithms or no algorithm at all.
1686.Description:
Nessus has detected that the remote SSH server is configured to use
the Arcfour stream cipher or no cipher at all. RFC 4253 advises
against using Arcfour due to an issue with weak keys.
1686.Solution:

ciphers.

1687.Name: Apache Tomcat 7.0.x < 7.0.82 / 8.5.x < 8.5.23 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1687.Synopsis:
The remote Apache Tomcat server is affected by a code execution
vulnerability.
1687.Description:
The version of Apache Tomcat installed on the remote host is 7.0.x
prior to 7.0.82 or 8.5.x prior to 8.5.23. It is, therefore, affected
by an unspecified vulnerability when running with HTTP PUTs enabled
(e.g. via setting the readonly initialization parameter of the Default
to false) that makes it possible to upload a JSP file to the server
via a specially crafted request. This JSP could then be requested and
any code it contained would be executed by the server.
Note that Nessus has not attempted to exploit this issue but has
instead relied only on the application's self-reported version number.
1687.Solution: Upgrade to Apache Tomcat version 7.0.82 / 8.5.23 or later.

1689.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
1689.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
1689.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
1689.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
1689.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

1699.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1699.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1699.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
1699.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

1706.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
1706.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
1706.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

1709.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
1709.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.

Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with

and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
1709.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.
1709.Plugin Output: TLSv1.1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

1713.Name: Apache Tomcat 8.0.x < 8.0.52 / 8.5.x < 8.5.31 / 9.0.x < 9.0.8 Denial of Service
1713.Synopsis:
The remote Apache Tomcat server is affected by a 
denial of service vulnerability.
1713.Description:
According to its self-reported version number, the Apache Tomcat
instance listening on the remote host is 8.0.x < 8.0.52, 
8.5.x < 8.5.31 or 9.0.x < 9.0.8. It is, therefore, affected 
by the following vulnerability:
  - A denial of service (DoS) vulnerability exists in 
    Tomcat due to improper overflow handling in the UTF-8
    decoder. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit 
    this issue to cause an infinite loop in the decoder,
    leading to a denial of service condition.
Note that Nessus has not tested for these issues but has instead
relied only on the application's self-reported version number.
1713.Solution: Upgrade to Apache Tomcat version 8.0.52 / 8.5.31 / 9.0.8 or later.

1716.Synopsis: The remote Apache Tomcat server is affected by a denial of service vulnerability
1716.Description:
The version of Tomcat installed on the remote host is prior to 8.5.41. It is, therefore, affected by a vulnerability as
referenced in the fixed_in_apache_tomcat_8.5.41_security-8 advisory.
  - The fix for CVE-2019-0199 was incomplete and did not
    address HTTP/2 connection window exhaustion on write. By
    not sending WINDOW_UPDATE messages for the connection
    window (stream 0) clients were able to cause server-side
    threads to block eventually leading to thread exhaustion
    and a DoS. (CVE-2019-10072)
Note that Nessus has not tested for this issue but has instead relied only on the application's self-reported version
number.
1716.Solution: Upgrade to Apache Tomcat version 8.5.41 or later.

1719.Name: Apache Tomcat 8.5.0 < 8.5.49 Privilege Escalation
1719.Synopsis: The remote Apache Tomcat server is affected by a vulnerability
1719.Description:
The version of Tomcat installed on the remote host is prior to 8.5.49. It is, therefore, affected by a vulnerability as
referenced in the fixed_in_apache_tomcat_8.5.49_security-8 advisory.
  - When Apache Tomcat is configured with the JMX Remote 
    Lifecycle Listener, a local attacker without access to 
    the Tomcat process or configuration files is able to 
    manipulate the RMI registry to perform a man-in-the-middle 
    attack to capture user names and passwords used to access 
    the JMX interface. The attacker can then use these 
    credentials to access the JMX interface and gain complete 
    control over the Tomcat instance. (CVE-2019-12418)
Note that Nessus has not tested for this issue but has instead relied only on the application's self-reported version
number.
1719.Solution: Upgrade to Apache Tomcat version 8.5.49 or later.

1723.Name: Apache Tomcat 7.0.x < 7.0.100 / 8.5.x < 8.5.51 / 9.0.x < 9.0.31 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1723.Synopsis: The remote Apache Tomcat server is affected by multiple vulnerabilities.
1723.Description:
The version of Tomcat installed on the remote host is 7.0.x prior to 7.0.100, 8.x prior to 8.5.51, or 9.0.x prior to 9.0.31. It
is, therefore, affected by multiple vulnerabilities.
  - An HTTP request smuggling vulnerability exists in Tomcat due to mishandling Transfer-Encoding headers
    behind a reverse proxy. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via crafted HTTP requests,
    to cause unintended HTTP requests to reach the back-end. (CVE-2019-17569)
  - An HTTP request smuggling vulnerability exists in Tomcat due to bad end-of-line (EOL) parsing that allowed
    some invalid HTTP headers to be parsed as valid. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via
    crafted HTTP requests, to cause unintended HTTP requests to reach the back-end. (CVE-2020-1935)
  - An arbitrary file read vulnerability exists in Tomcat's Apache JServ Protocol (AJP) due to an
    implementation defect. A remote, unauthenticated attacker could exploit this to access files which, under
    normal conditions, would be restricted. If the Tomcat instance supports file uploads, the vulnerability
    could also be leveraged to achieve remote code execution. (CVE-2020-1938)
Note that Nessus has not tested for this issue but has instead relied only on the application's self-reported version 
number.
1723.Solution: Upgrade to Apache Tomcat version 7.0.100, 8.5.51, 9.0.31 or later.

1738.Name: Apache Tomcat 8.5.0 < 8.5.57 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1738.Synopsis: The remote Apache Tomcat server is affected by multiple vulnerabilities
1738.Description:
The version of Tomcat installed on the remote host is 8.5.x prior to 8.5.57. It is, therefore, affected by multiple
vulnerabilities as referenced in the Fixed in Apache Tomcat 8.5.57 security advisory.
  - The payload length in a WebSocket frame was not correctly validated. Invalid payload lengths could trigger
    an infinite loop. Multiple requests with invalid payload lengths could lead to a denial of service (DoS).
    (CVE-2020-13935)
  - An h2c direct connection did not release the HTTP/1.1 processor after the upgrade to HTTP/2. If a
    sufficient number of such requests were made, an OutOfMemoryException could occur leading to a denial of
    service (DoS). (CVE-2020-13934)
Note that Nessus has not tested for this issue but has instead relied only on the application's self-reported version
number.
1738.Solution: Upgrade to Apache Tomcat version 8.5.57 or later.

1742.Name: Apache Tomcat 8.5.x < 8.5.58 / 9.0.x < 9.0.38 HTTP/2 Request Mix-Up
1742.Synopsis: The remote Apache Tomcat server is affected by a vulnerability
1742.Description:
The version of Tomcat installed on the remote host is 8.5.x prior to 8.5.58 or 9.0.x prior to 9.0.38. It is, therefore,
affected by a vulnerability. If an HTTP/2 client exceeds the agreed maximum number of concurrent streams for a
connection (in violation of the HTTP/2 protocol), it is possible that a subsequent request made on that connection could
contain HTTP headers - including HTTP/2 pseudo headers - from a previous request rather than the intended headers. This
can lead to users seeing responses for unexpected resources.
Note that Nessus has not tested for this issue but has instead relied only on the application's self-reported version
number.
1742.Solution: Upgrade to Apache Tomcat version 8.5.58, 9.0.38 or later.

1744.Name: Apache Tomcat 8.5.x < 8.5.60 Information Disclosure
1744.Synopsis: The remote Apache Tomcat server is affected by an information disclosure vulnerability.
1744.Description:
The version of Tomcat installed on the remote host is prior to 8.5.60. It is, therefore, affected by multiple
vulnerabilities as referenced in the fixed_in_apache_tomcat_8.5.60_security-8 advisory.
  - When serving resources from a network location using the NTFS file system, Apache Tomcat versions
    10.0.0-M1 to 10.0.0-M9, 9.0.0.M1 to 9.0.39, 8.5.0 to 8.5.59 and 7.0.0 to 7.0.106 were susceptible to JSP
    source code disclosure in some configurations. The root cause was the unexpected behaviour of the JRE API
    File.getCanonicalPath() which in turn was caused by the inconsistent behaviour of the Windows API
    (FindFirstFileW) in some circumstances. (CVE-2021-24122)
  - While investigating bug 64830 it was discovered that Apache Tomcat 10.0.0-M1 to 10.0.0-M9, 9.0.0-M1 to
    9.0.39 and 8.5.0 to 8.5.59 could re-use an HTTP request header value from the previous stream received on
    an HTTP/2 connection for the request associated with the subsequent stream. While this would most likely
    lead to an error and the closure of the HTTP/2 connection, it is possible that information could leak
    between requests. (CVE-2020-17527)
Note that Nessus has not tested for this issue but has instead relied only on the application's self-reported version
number.
1744.Solution: Upgrade to Apache Tomcat version 8.5.60 or later.

vulnerabilities as referenced in the fixed_in_apache_tomcat_8.5.60_security-8 advisory.
  - When serving resources from a network location using the NTFS file system, Apache Tomcat versions
    10.0.0-M1 to 10.0.0-M9, 9.0.0.M1 to 9.0.39, 8.5.0 to 8.5.59 and 7.0.0 to 7.0.106 were susceptible to JSP
    source code disclosure in some configurations. The root cause was the unexpected behaviour of the JRE API
    File.getCanonicalPath() which in turn was caused by the inconsistent behaviour of the Windows API
    (FindFirstFileW) in some circumstances. (CVE-2021-24122)
  - While investigating bug 64830 it was discovered that Apache Tomcat 10.0.0-M1 to 10.0.0-M9, 9.0.0-M1 to
    9.0.39 and 8.5.0 to 8.5.59 could re-use an HTTP request header value from the previous stream received on
    an HTTP/2 connection for the request associated with the subsequent stream. While this would most likely
    lead to an error and the closure of the HTTP/2 connection, it is possible that information could leak
    between requests. (CVE-2020-17527)
Note that Nessus has not tested for this issue but has instead relied only on the application's self-reported version
number.
1746.Solution: Upgrade to Apache Tomcat version 8.5.60 or later.

1748.Name: Apache Tomcat 8.5.0 < 8.5.63 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1748.Synopsis: The remote Apache Tomcat server is affected by multiple vulnerabilities
1748.Description:
The version of Tomcat installed on the remote host is prior to 8.5.63. It is, therefore, affected by multiple
vulnerabilities as referenced in the vendor advisory.
  - When responding to new h2c connection requests, Apache Tomcat versions 10.0.0-M1 to 10.0.0, 9.0.0.M1 to 9.0.41 
    and 8.5.0 to 8.5.61 could duplicate request headers and a limited amount of request body from one request to 
    another meaning user A and user B could both see the results of user A's request. (CVE-2021-25122)
  - When using Apache Tomcat 10.0.0-M1 to 10.0.0, 9.0.0.M1 to 9.0.41, 8.5.0 to 8.5.61 or 7.0.0. to 7.0.107 with a 
    configuration edge case that was highly unlikely to be used, the Tomcat instance was still vulnerable to 
    CVE-2020-9494. Note that both the previously published prerequisites for CVE-2020-9484 and the previously 
    published mitigations for CVE-2020-9484 also apply to this issue. (CVE-2021-25329)
Note that Nessus has not tested for this issue but has instead relied only on the application's self-reported version
number.
1748.Solution: Upgrade to Apache Tomcat version 8.5.63 or later.

1753.Name: Apache Tomcat 7.0.x <= 7.0.108 / 8.5.x <= 8.5.65 / 9.0.x <= 9.0.45 / 10.0.x <= 10.0.5 vulnerability
1753.Synopsis: The remote Apache Tomcat server is affected by a vulnerability
1753.Description:
The version of Tomcat installed on the remote host is 7.0.x <= 7.0.108 / 8.5.x <= 8.5.65 / 9.0.x <= 9.0.45 / 10.0.x <= 
10.0.5. It is, therefore, affected by a vulnerability as referenced in the fixed_in_apache_tomcat_10.0.6_security-10 
advisory.
  - Queries made by the JNDI Realm did not always correctly escape parameters. Parameter values could be
    sourced from user provided data (eg user names) as well as configuration data provided by an
    administrator. In limited circumstances it was possible for users to authenticate using variations of
    their user name and/or to bypass some of the protection provided by the LockOut Realm. (CVE-2021-30640)
Note that Nessus has not tested for this issue but has instead relied only on the application's self-reported version
number.
1753.Solution: Upgrade to Apache Tomcat version 7.0.109, 8.5.66, 9.0.46, 10.0.6 or later.

1755.Name: Apache Tomcat 8.5.0 < 8.5.68 vulnerability
1755.Synopsis: The remote Apache Tomcat server is affected by a vulnerability
1755.Description:
The version of Tomcat installed on the remote host is prior to 8.5.68. It is, therefore, affected by a vulnerability as
referenced in the fixed_in_apache_tomcat_8.5.68_security-8 advisory.
  - Apache Tomcat 10.0.0-M1 to 10.0.6, 9.0.0.M1 to 9.0.46 and 8.5.0 to 8.5.66 did not correctly parse the HTTP
    transfer-encoding request header in some circumstances leading to the possibility to request smuggling
    when used with a reverse proxy. Specifically: - Tomcat incorrectly ignored the transfer encoding header if
    the client declared it would only accept an HTTP/1.0 response; - Tomcat honoured the identify encoding;
    and - Tomcat did not ensure that, if present, the chunked encoding was the final encoding.
    (CVE-2021-33037)
Note that Nessus has not tested for this issue but has instead relied only on the application's self-reported version
number.
1755.Solution: Upgrade to Apache Tomcat version 8.5.68 or later.

1757.Name: SSH SHA-1 HMAC Algorithms Enabled
1757.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
1757.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
Although NIST has formally deprecated use of SHA-1 for digital signatures, SHA-1 is still considered secure for HMAC as
the security of HMAC does not rely on the underlying hash function being resistant to collisions.
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the remote SSH server.
1757.Plugin Output:
The following client-to-server SHA-1 Hash-based Message Authentication Code (HMAC) algorithms are supported : 
  hmac-sha1
  hmac-sha1-96
  hmac-sha1-96-etm@openssh.com
  hmac-sha1-etm@openssh.com
The following server-to-client SHA-1 Hash-based Message Authentication Code (HMAC) algorithms are supported : 
  hmac-sha1
  hmac-sha1-96
  hmac-sha1-96-etm@openssh.com
  hmac-sha1-etm@openssh.com

1758.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
1758.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
1758.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
  gss-gex-sha1-*
  gss-group1-sha1-*
  gss-group14-sha1-*
  rsa1024-sha1
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.
1758.Solution: Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable the weak algorithms.
1758.Plugin Output:
The following weak key exchange algorithms are enabled : 
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1

1759.Name: SSL/TLS Recommended Cipher Suites
1759.Synopsis: The remote host advertises discouraged SSL/TLS ciphers.
1759.Description:
The remote host has open SSL/TLS ports which advertise discouraged cipher suites. It is recommended to only enable
support for the following cipher suites:
TLSv1.3:
  - 0x13,0x01 TLS_AES_128_GCM_SHA256
  - 0x13,0x02 TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384
  - 0x13,0x03 TLS_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256
TLSv1.2:
  - 0xC0,0x2B ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0xC0,0x2F ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0xC0,0x2C ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
  - 0xC0,0x30 ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
  - 0xCC,0xA9 ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305
  - 0xCC,0xA8 ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305
  - 0x00,0x9E DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0x00,0x9F DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
This is the recommended configuration for the vast majority of services, as it is highly secure and compatible with
nearly every client released in the last five (or more) years.
1759.Solution: Only enable support for recommened cipher suites.

1765.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1765.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1765.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.
Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1765.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
1765.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is -1 seconds.

firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.

1810.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
1810.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
1810.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
1810.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
1810.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : CN=APM_MIN_server
|-Issuer  : CN=APM_MIN_server

1829.Name: Web Application Cookies Are Expired
1829.Synopsis:
HTTP cookies have an 'Expires' attribute that is set with a past date
or time.
1829.Description:
The remote web application sets various cookies throughout a user's
unauthenticated and authenticated session. However, Nessus has
detected that one or more of the cookies have an 'Expires' attribute
that is set with a past date or time, meaning that these cookies will
be removed by the browser.
1829.Solution:
Each cookie should be carefully reviewed to determine if it contains
sensitive data or is relied upon for a security decision.
If needed, set an expiration date in the future so the cookie will
persist or remove the Expires cookie attribute altogether to convert
the cookie to a session cookie.

1832.Name: Web Application Cookies Are Expired
1832.Synopsis:
HTTP cookies have an 'Expires' attribute that is set with a past date
or time.
1832.Description:
The remote web application sets various cookies throughout a user's
unauthenticated and authenticated session. However, Nessus has
detected that one or more of the cookies have an 'Expires' attribute
that is set with a past date or time, meaning that these cookies will
be removed by the browser.
1832.Solution:
Each cookie should be carefully reviewed to determine if it contains
sensitive data or is relied upon for a security decision.
If needed, set an expiration date in the future so the cookie will
persist or remove the Expires cookie attribute altogether to convert
the cookie to a session cookie.

1833.Name: Apache Zookeeper Server Detection

1834.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1834.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1834.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
1834.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

1835.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
1835.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
1835.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

1836.Name: MongoDB 2.x, 3.0.x < 3.0.15, 3.1.x < 3.2.14, 3.3.x < 3.3.14 Mongo Shell Information Disclosure Vulnerability (SERVER-25335)
1836.Synopsis: The remote database server is affected by an information disclosure  vulnerability.
1836.Description:
The version of the remote MongoDB server is 2.x, 3.x < 3.0.15, 3.2.x < 3.2.14, 3.3.x < 3.3.14. It is, therefore,
affected by an information disclosure in mongo shell due to the MongoDB client having world-readable permissions on 
.dbshell history files. An unauthenticated, local attacker can exploit this by reading these files to disclose 
potentially sensitive information.
Note that Nessus has not tested for these issues but has instead relied only on the application's self-reported version
number.
1836.Solution: Upgrade to MongoDB version 3.0.15, 3.2.14, 3.3.14, 3.4 or later.

1840.Name: SSH SHA-1 HMAC Algorithms Enabled
1840.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
1840.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
Although NIST has formally deprecated use of SHA-1 for digital signatures, SHA-1 is still considered secure for HMAC as
the security of HMAC does not rely on the underlying hash function being resistant to collisions.
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the remote SSH server.

  hmac-sha1-96-etm@openssh.com
  hmac-sha1-etm@openssh.com
The following server-to-client SHA-1 Hash-based Message Authentication Code (HMAC) algorithms are supported :

1841.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
1841.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
1841.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
  gss-gex-sha1-*
  gss-group1-sha1-*
  gss-group14-sha1-*
  rsa1024-sha1
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.
1841.Solution: Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable the weak algorithms.
1841.Plugin Output:
The following weak key exchange algorithms are enabled : 
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1

1842.Name: SSL/TLS Recommended Cipher Suites
1842.Synopsis: The remote host advertises discouraged SSL/TLS ciphers.
1842.Description:
The remote host has open SSL/TLS ports which advertise discouraged cipher suites. It is recommended to only enable
support for the following cipher suites:
TLSv1.3:
  - 0x13,0x01 TLS_AES_128_GCM_SHA256
  - 0x13,0x02 TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384
  - 0x13,0x03 TLS_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256
TLSv1.2:
  - 0xC0,0x2B ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0xC0,0x2F ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0xC0,0x2C ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
  - 0xC0,0x30 ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
  - 0xCC,0xA9 ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305
  - 0xCC,0xA8 ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305
  - 0x00,0x9E DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0x00,0x9F DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
This is the recommended configuration for the vast majority of services, as it is highly secure and compatible with
nearly every client released in the last five (or more) years.
1842.Solution: Only enable support for recommened cipher suites.

1846.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1846.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1846.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.
Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1846.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
1846.Plugin Output: The remote clock is synchronized with the local clock.

1847.Name: HTTP Proxy Open Relay Detection
1847.Synopsis: The remote web proxy server accepts requests.
1847.Description:
The remote web proxy accepts unauthenticated HTTP requests from the
Nessus scanner.  By routing requests through the affected proxy, a user
may be able to gain some degree of anonymity while browsing websites,
which will see requests as originating from the remote host itself
rather than the user's host.
1847.Solution: Make sure access to the proxy is limited to valid users / hosts.

1848.Name: HTTP Proxy Open Relay Detection
1848.Synopsis: The remote web proxy server accepts requests.
1848.Description:
The remote web proxy accepts unauthenticated HTTP requests from the
Nessus scanner.  By routing requests through the affected proxy, a user
may be able to gain some degree of anonymity while browsing websites,
which will see requests as originating from the remote host itself
rather than the user's host.
1848.Solution: Make sure access to the proxy is limited to valid users / hosts.

1877.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
1877.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
1877.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
1877.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
1877.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : C=US/O=IBM/CN=IBM Tivoli Monitoring Self-Signed Certificate
|-Issuer  : C=US/O=IBM/CN=IBM Tivoli Monitoring Self-Signed Certificate

1887.Synopsis: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS.
1887.Description:
The remote HTTPS server is not enforcing HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS). 
HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
1887.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.
1887.Plugin Output:
The remote HTTPS server does not send the HTTP
  "Strict-Transport-Security" header.

1888.Name: SSH Weak Algorithms Supported
1888.Synopsis:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak encryption
algorithms or no algorithm at all.
1888.Description:
Nessus has detected that the remote SSH server is configured to use
the Arcfour stream cipher or no cipher at all. RFC 4253 advises
against using Arcfour due to an issue with weak keys.
1888.Solution:
Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to remove the weak
ciphers.
1888.Plugin Output:
The following weak server-to-client encryption algorithms are supported : 
  arcfour
  arcfour128
  arcfour256
The following weak client-to-server encryption algorithms are supported : 
  arcfour
  arcfour128
  arcfour256

1889.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
1889.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
1889.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
1889.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
1889.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

1890.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1890.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1890.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
1890.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

1891.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
1891.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
1891.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.
1891.Plugin Output:
The following issues were reported :
  - Plugin      : no_local_checks_credentials.nasl
    Plugin ID   : 110723
    Plugin Name : Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
    Message     : 
Credentials were not provided for detected SSH service.

1892.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
1892.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
1892.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
1892.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.
1892.Plugin Output: TLSv1.1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

1893.Name: TLS Version 1.2 Protocol Detection
1893.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using a version of TLS.
1893.Description: The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.2.
1893.Plugin Output: TLSv1.2 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

1894.Name: SSH Password Authentication Accepted
1894.Synopsis: The SSH server on the remote host accepts password authentication.
1894.Description: The SSH server on the remote host accepts password authentication.

1895.Name: SSH SHA-1 HMAC Algorithms Enabled
1895.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
1895.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to enable SHA-1 HMAC algorithms.
Although NIST has formally deprecated use of SHA-1 for digital signatures, SHA-1 is still considered secure for HMAC as
the security of HMAC does not rely on the underlying hash function being resistant to collisions.
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the remote SSH server.

The following client-to-server SHA-1 Hash-based Message Authentication Code (HMAC) algorithms are supported : 
  hmac-sha1
  hmac-sha1-96
The following server-to-client SHA-1 Hash-based Message Authentication Code (HMAC) algorithms are supported : 
  hmac-sha1
  hmac-sha1-96

1896.Name: SSH Weak Key Exchange Algorithms Enabled
1896.Synopsis: The remote SSH server is configured to allow weak key exchange algorithms.
1896.Description:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow key exchange algorithms which are considered weak.
This is based on the IETF draft document Key Exchange (KEX) Method Updates and Recommendations for Secure Shell (SSH)
draft-ietf-curdle-ssh-kex-sha2-20. Section 4 lists guidance on key exchange algorithms that SHOULD NOT and MUST NOT be
enabled. This includes:
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
  gss-gex-sha1-*
  gss-group1-sha1-*
  gss-group14-sha1-*
  rsa1024-sha1
Note that this plugin only checks for the options of the SSH server, and it does not check for vulnerable software
versions.
1896.Solution: Contact the vendor or consult product documentation to disable the weak algorithms.
1896.Plugin Output:
The following weak key exchange algorithms are enabled : 
  diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
  diffie-hellman-group1-sha1

1897.Name: SSL/TLS Recommended Cipher Suites
1897.Synopsis: The remote host advertises discouraged SSL/TLS ciphers.
1897.Description:
The remote host has open SSL/TLS ports which advertise discouraged cipher suites. It is recommended to only enable
support for the following cipher suites:
TLSv1.3:
  - 0x13,0x01 TLS_AES_128_GCM_SHA256
  - 0x13,0x02 TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384
  - 0x13,0x03 TLS_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256
TLSv1.2:
  - 0xC0,0x2B ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0xC0,0x2F ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0xC0,0x2C ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
  - 0xC0,0x30 ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
  - 0xCC,0xA9 ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305
  - 0xCC,0xA8 ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305
  - 0x00,0x9E DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0x00,0x9F DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
This is the recommended configuration for the vast majority of services, as it is highly secure and compatible with
nearly every client released in the last five (or more) years.
1897.Solution: Only enable support for recommened cipher suites.

1900.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1900.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1900.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.
Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1900.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
1900.Plugin Output: The remote clock is synchronized with the local clock.

1909.Name: Nessus SYN scanner
1909.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.
1909.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 
Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.

1917.Name: SSL Version 2 and 3 Protocol Detection
1917.Synopsis:
The remote service encrypts traffic using a protocol with known
weaknesses.
1917.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using SSL 2.0 and/or
SSL 3.0. These versions of SSL are affected by several cryptographic
flaws, including:
  - An insecure padding scheme with CBC ciphers.
  - Insecure session renegotiation and resumption schemes.
An attacker can exploit these flaws to conduct man-in-the-middle
attacks or to decrypt communications between the affected service and
clients.
Although SSL/TLS has a secure means for choosing the highest supported
version of the protocol (so that these versions will be used only if
the client or server support nothing better), many web browsers
implement this in an unsafe way that allows an attacker to downgrade
a connection (such as in POODLE). Therefore, it is recommended that
these protocols be disabled entirely.
NIST has determined that SSL 3.0 is no longer acceptable for secure
communications. As of the date of enforcement found in PCI DSS v3.1,
any version of SSL will not meet the PCI SSC's definition of 'strong
cryptography'.
1917.Solution:
Consult the application's documentation to disable SSL 2.0 and 3.0.
Use TLS 1.2 (with approved cipher suites) or higher instead.

1927.Name: SSL Medium Strength Cipher Suites Supported (SWEET32)
1927.Synopsis: The remote service supports the use of medium strength SSL ciphers.
1927.Description:
The remote host supports the use of SSL ciphers that offer medium
strength encryption. Nessus regards medium strength as any encryption
that uses key lengths at least 64 bits and less than 112 bits, or 
else that uses the 3DES encryption suite.
Note that it is considerably easier to circumvent medium strength
encryption if the attacker is on the same physical network.
1927.Solution:

medium strength ciphers.

1931.Name: OpenSSL Detection
1931.Synopsis: The remote service appears to use OpenSSL to encrypt traffic.

server name extension, it seems that the remote service is using the
OpenSSL library to encrypt traffic.
Note that this plugin can only detect OpenSSL implementations that
have enabled support for TLS extensions (RFC 4366).

1932.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
1932.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
1932.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
1932.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
1932.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was part of the certificate chain
sent by the remote host, but it has expired :
|-Subject   : C=--/ST=SomeState/L=SomeCity/O=SomeOrganization/OU=SomeOrganizationalUnit/CN=localhost/E=root@localhost
|-Not After : Oct 31 13:31:11 2018 GMT
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : C=--/ST=SomeState/L=SomeCity/O=SomeOrganization/OU=SomeOrganizationalUnit/CN=localhost/E=root@localhost
|-Issuer  : C=--/ST=SomeState/L=SomeCity/O=SomeOrganization/OU=SomeOrganizationalUnit/CN=localhost/E=root@localhost

1933.Name: SSL Session Resume Supported
1933.Synopsis: The remote host allows resuming SSL sessions.
1933.Description:

performing a full SSL handshake to receive a session ID, and then
reconnecting with the previously used session ID.  If the server
accepts the session ID in the second connection, the server maintains
a cache of sessions that can be resumed.

1940.Name: SSL RC4 Cipher Suites Supported (Bar Mitzvah)
1940.Synopsis: The remote service supports the use of the RC4 cipher.
1940.Description:
The remote host supports the use of RC4 in one or more cipher suites.
The RC4 cipher is flawed in its generation of a pseudo-random stream
of bytes so that a wide variety of small biases are introduced into
the stream, decreasing its randomness.
If plaintext is repeatedly encrypted (e.g., HTTP cookies), and an
attacker is able to obtain many (i.e., tens of millions) ciphertexts,
the attacker may be able to derive the plaintext.
1940.Solution:
Reconfigure the affected application, if possible, to avoid use of RC4
ciphers. Consider using TLS 1.2 with AES-GCM suites subject to browser
and web server support.

1944.Name: HSTS Missing From HTTPS Server
1944.Synopsis: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS.
1944.Description:
The remote HTTPS server is not enforcing HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS). 
HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
1944.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.
1944.Plugin Output:
The remote HTTPS server does not send the HTTP
  "Strict-Transport-Security" header.

1945.Name: TLS NPN Supported Protocol Enumeration
1945.Synopsis: The remote host supports the TLS NPN extension.
1945.Description:
The remote host supports the TLS NPN (Transport Layer Security Next
Protocol Negotiation) extension. This plugin enumerates the protocols
the extension supports.

1946.Name: OpenSSL AES-NI Padding Oracle MitM Information Disclosure
1946.Synopsis:
It was possible to obtain sensitive information from the remote host
with TLS-enabled services.
1946.Description:
The remote host is affected by a man-in-the-middle (MitM) information
disclosure vulnerability due to an error in the implementation of
ciphersuites that use AES in CBC mode with HMAC-SHA1 or HMAC-SHA256.
The implementation is specially written to use the AES acceleration
available in x86/amd64 processors (AES-NI). The error messages
returned by the server allow allow a man-in-the-middle attacker to
conduct a padding oracle attack, resulting in the ability to decrypt
network traffic.
1946.Solution: Upgrade to OpenSSL version 1.0.1t / 1.0.2h or later.
1946.Plugin Output:
Nessus was able to trigger a RECORD_OVERFLOW alert in the
remote service by sending a crafted SSL "Finished" message.

1947.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
1947.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
1947.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
1947.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
1947.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

1948.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
1948.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
1948.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1
As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
1948.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.
1948.Plugin Output: TLSv1.1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

1949.Name: TLS Version 1.2 Protocol Detection
1949.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using a version of TLS.
1949.Description: The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.2.

1951.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1951.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1951.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.
Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1951.Solution:

timestamp replies (14).

1965.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
1965.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
1965.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

authentication protocols.

2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.

timestamp replies (14).

channel.
Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.
SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.

2005.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
2005.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
2005.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.
Please note the following :
- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.
- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
2005.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

2006.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
2006.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
2006.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.
This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

2010.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
2010.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
2010.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.
Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
2010.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
2010.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 41353 seconds.

2016.Name: Nessus SYN scanner

2016.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 
Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
2016.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.

2032.Name: FTP Service AUTH TLS Command Support
2032.Synopsis: The remote directory service supports encrypting traffic.
2032.Description:
The remote FTP service supports the use of the 'AUTH TLS' command to
switch from a cleartext to an encrypted communications channel.
2032.Plugin Output:
The remote FTP service responded to the 'AUTH TLS' command with a
'234' response code, suggesting that it supports that command.  However,
Nessus failed to negotiate a TLS connection or get the associated SSL
certificate, perhaps because of a network connectivity problem or the
service requires a peer certificate as part of the negotiation.

2033.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
2033.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
2033.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.
Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.
SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
2033.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

The remote web server type is :
Apache

2048.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
2048.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
2048.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.
Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
2048.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
2048.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is -1 seconds.

2049.Name: SSH Server Type and Version Information
2049.Synopsis: An SSH server is listening on this port.
2049.Description:
It is possible to obtain information about the remote SSH server by
sending an empty authentication request.

SSH version : SSH-2.0-OpenSSH_7.4
SSH supported authentication : publickey,gssapi-keyex,gssapi-with-mic,password

2051.Name: Web Server No 404 Error Code Check
2051.Synopsis: The remote web server does not return 404 error codes.
2051.Description:
The remote web server is configured such that it does not return '404
Not Found' error codes when a nonexistent file is requested, perhaps
returning instead a site map, search page or authentication page.
Nessus has enabled some counter measures for this.  However, they
might be insufficient.  If a great number of security holes are
produced for this port, they might not all be accurate.

CGI scanning will be disabled for this host because the host responds
to requests for non-existent URLs with HTTP code 302
rather than 404. The requested URL was : 
    http://172.16.1.2/4WvpTlKD1FrP.html

2099.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
2099.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
2099.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :
  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
2099.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
2099.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : CN=inetpowervcdc
|-Issuer  : CN=inetpowervcdc

    chain to a known public certificate authority.
  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.
  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.
If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
2103.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :
|-Subject : CN=inetpowervcdc
|-Issuer  : CN=inetpowervcdc

2127.Name: HSTS Missing From HTTPS Server
2127.Synopsis: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS.
2127.Description:
The remote HTTPS server is not enforcing HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS). 
HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
2127.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.

  "Strict-Transport-Security" header.

2132.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
2132.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
2132.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
2132.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

2133.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
2133.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
2133.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.

This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

2166.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
2166.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
2166.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
2166.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.
